observations.recommendation:
We recommended that Management:
Require the MGSO and MAO to undertake the reconciliation of RPCI/stock cards with the records of the MAO;
Require the MGSO to –
Regularly update the recording in the stock cards for all the Inventory accounts as basis of reporting the correct amount of Inventory;
Maintain stock cards for all supplies, and for MAO to update regularly the subsidiary ledgers of supplies as the basis of reporting the correct amount of Inventory;
Waste Material Report shall be rendered on expired inventory items for submission to MAO for inventory adjustments purposes; and
Require the MAO to maintain SLC records for all the inventory accounts and regularly update the recording to SLCs for purposes of monitoring the quantity and costing movement of inventories.

We commended Management for exceeding its revenue projections for the year.

We still recommended that Management, through the LFC, to:
Consider a systematic and realistic forecasting of revenue taking into account the prior years’ experience and statistics as aids in setting targets;
Involve the MTO, Business Permit and Licensing Office (BPLO) and other Departments in generating revenues to meet its targets;
Require the MTO to coordinate with the LFC the initiated Quarterly Report of Income as basis to keep track of the status of revenue generation; and
Require the concerned officials to conduct periodic review of the Quarterly Report of Income to ascertain whether collection targets are attained, and to provide assurance of improved finances for the operations of the Municipality.

In view of the foregoing, we recommended that the Management to –
Comply the requirements of Section 20 of COA Circular No. 2002-003 dated June 20, 2002, or MNGAS for LGUs, Volume I, and as provided in the Contract Agreement, to coordinate with the Service Integrator for compliance on the following:
Agreement on the standards and procedures for testing and acceptance of the PILGUS specifying definite timetable within which to accomplish the validation testing of financial transactions and generation of reports/records for purposes of reconciliation and/or establishment of correct database build-up that will support the correct Certified List of Taxpayers and RPT Delinquency Reports;
To generate complete information on HRIS reports/records of DTRs, Monthly Report on Tardiness, and Undertime, Employee Overtime, and Employee Leave Ledger Card;
Direct coordination between Offices of the Municipal Assessor, Municipal Treasurer and Municipal Accountant particularly on:
Acceptance of the Municipal Assessor as process owner of data for the assessed value of real property after adopting the reconciliation facility of data converted from manual to automated information system maintained by the Assessor for the RPTAS;
Acceptance of the Municipal Treasurer as process owner of data on the collectible RPT/SET after adopting the reconciliation facility of data converted from manual to automated information system on the taxable RPUs;
Acknowledgement of the Municipal Accounting Office for the correct Certified List of Taxpayers and RPT Delinquency Reports as basis in the recording of RPT/SET Receivables at the beginning and end of the year;
Comply with the preparation and submission of Status and/or monitoring reports to keep track of the performance and compliance of the Systems Integrator on the RPTAS, HIRS deliverables as well as keeping track the agreed computer fees the Municipality is obliged to settle for the Systems Integrator’s services; and
Require the submission on the amendatory provisions of the contract specifying the revised timetable on the project’s implementation and target completion date.

Consider a systematic and realistic forecasting of revenue taking into account the prior years’ experience and statistics as aids in setting targets;
Involve the MTO and other Departments in generating revenues to meet its targets;
Require the MTO to accomplish the Quarterly Report of Income to keep track of the status of revenue generation; and
Require the concerned officials to conduct periodic review of the Quarterly Report of Income to ascertain whether collection targets are attained, and to provide assurance of improved finances for the operations of the Municipality.

We recommended that Management

Maximize the utilization of the 20% Development Fund thru proper planning so that all programmed development projects during the year could be fully implemented for the benefit of the Municipality’s constituents;

Direct the Municipal Planning Development Coordinator which prepared the 20% Development Fund and the Municipal Budget Officer to take into consideration the pertinent provisions of JMC 2011-1 of the DBM and DILG in the preparation of the Executive Annual Budget, AIP and Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) of the Municipality. The utilization of the 20% Development Fund partakes the nature of investment or capital expenditures, as such cost recovery and entrepreneurship should be taken into consideration; 

Require the Municipal Engineer to execute all projects planned for implementation during the year and submit accomplishment reports on a monthly or quarterly basis to the Municipal Planning Development Coordinator for monitoring and evaluation;


Direct the Municipal Planning Development Coordinator to properly monitor and evaluate the implementation of projects and submit periodic reports to the Office of the Municipal Mayor incorporating issues and concerns affecting the execution of projects; and

Require the concerned Municipal officials to facilitate the preparation of the CDP and LDIP to comply with JMC No. 1 series of 2007.  Identification of PPAs for medium term plan will boost management capability to identify development projects that will truly address the socio-economic development and environmental management of the municipality. 

We also recommended that the Municipal Mayor ensure that the 20% Development Fund is utilized exclusively for the development projects provided under DILG-DBM JMC No. 2011-1.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Accountant and the Municipal General Services Officer:
Analyze/reconcile the SLs and RPCPPE to fully account for the municipal assets and to determine the fair value of PPE accounts for reliable presentation in the financial statements;
Effect proper valuation of donated property in their respective PPE Ledger Card and Property Card;
The Municipal Mayor create a Disposal and Appraisal Committee responsible for the determination of present value and remaining useful life of all donated property, including those properties found in station without cost;
The Municipal Accountant to:
Effect the necessary adjusting entries to drop the carrying value of semi-expendable property costing below P15,000.00 by debiting the Accumulated Depreciation, debiting the Prior Year’s Adjustment account and crediting the proper asset account.
Henceforth, all property costing below the prevailing capitalization threshold amount of P15,000.00 should be recorded  under the related expense accounts and be covered by Inventory Custodian Slip (ICS) upon issuance to the end-user;
Transfer all PPE accounts under the Trust Fund books to the General Fund books in compliance with the NGAS Manual so as to provide adequate depreciation for proper valuation in the books of accounts; and
The MGSO prepare the Inventory and Inspection of Unserviceable Property (IIRUP) for the demolished building and subsequently submit the same to the Municipal Accountant to substantiate the dropping of asset from the books.

We recommended that:
The Municipal Mayor and Municipal Treasurer make representation with concerned officials of  MERALCO and PLDT to verify the status of outstanding  investment made by the Municipality amounting to P0.258 million;
The Municipal Treasurer:
Determine the amount of accrued dividend/interest on the investment in stocks ;
Secure copy of  stock certificates to obtain proof of ownership of said investments; and
The Municipal Accountant effect the adjustments as necessary, to reflect the correct balance of Investment in Stocks account in the financial statements.

We recommended that Management :
Maximize the utilization of the 20% MDF thru proper planning so that all programmed development projects during the year could be fully implemented for the benefit of the Municipality’s constituents;
Direct the Municipal Planning Development Coordinator, which prepared the plan for the 20% MDF, and the Municipal Budget Officer to take into consideration the pertinent provisions of 
JMC 2017-1 of the DBM and DILG in the preparation of the Executive Annual Budget, AIP and Project Procurement Management Plan (PPMP) of the Municipality. The utilization of the 20% MDF partakes the nature of investment or capital expenditures, as such cost recovery and entrepreneurship should be taken into consideration;
Direct the Municipal Planning Development Coordinator to properly monitor and evaluate the implementation of projects and submit periodic reports to the Office of the Municipal Mayor incorporating issues and concerns affecting the execution of projects;
Require the Municipal Accountant to maintain a separate special account in the General Fund for the 20% MDF and provide complete subsidiary ledger to have adequate information as to the assets, liabilities and equity; and
The Municipal Mayor ensure that the 20% MDF is utilized exclusively for the development projects provided under DILG-DBM JMC No. 2011-1.

